      {
        "id": 263577,
        "name": "",
        "username": "Herohtar",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/community.signalusers.org/herohtar/{size}/43780_2.png",
        "created_at": "2025-03-14T17:35:54.336Z",
        "cooked": "<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"roscoe\" data-post=\"4\" data-topic=\"67672\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n<img alt=\"\" width=\"24\" height=\"24\" src=\"https://community.signalusers.org/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/r/258eb7/48.png\" class=\"avatar\"> roscoe:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<p>All I have is phone numbers for a number of friends</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>If they are registered with Signal using those phone numbers and haven’t entirely disabled discoverability then all you need to do is initiate a Signal chat with them. They will neither see nor need your phone number (if <em>you</em> have discoverability turned off) nor your username.</p>\n<p>They will get a message request since you’ll be a new unknown contact and will have to choose to believe you and accept your request.</p>\n<p>Otherwise, if you don’t have a valid Signal identifier for them, you cannot contact them via Signal.</p>",
